[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287250"]

1. e4 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 
1... e5 {, the Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The 
majority of Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large 
role, theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can 
also be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of 
dodging the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is 
by far White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open 
Sicilian. The Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the 
critical test to all Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and 
typically require plenty of memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for 
an Anti-Sicilian. Their primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in 
mainline Sicilians and as a result they usually are especially popular amongst 
club players. We'll be examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines 
of this course.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4][%csl Gc6]} ({This move 
characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... a6 {leads to the 
Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in the Kan the queen's 
knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas in the Taimanov the 
knight heads for c6.}) 5. Be3 {[%cal Bc2c4] This is in fact White's third most 
common move, which is surprising since it isn't very good. White was probably 
angling for a Maroczy bind (with c4) but this falls flat on its face in a 
similar way to early Be3 ideas do in the Sicilian Kan.} Nf6 $1 {[%cal 
Gf6e4][%csl Re4] 5. Be3 left the e4-pawn exposed.} 6. Nc3 {This is almost like a 
regular English Attack position - the variation with 5. Nc3 and 6. Be3 which is 
covered in a later chapter - except Black has got the chance to play ...Nf6 
instead of ...Qc7. As a result Black can take the initiative right out of the 
opening.} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Re4,Rc3,Re1] An unpleasant pin which 
reinforces the threat to White's e4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 {Defending e4, albeit 
awkardly.} d5 $11 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gf6d5,Gb4e1][%csl Re4,Rc3,Re1] By carrying out 
this central break Black frees his pieces and fully equalises - in fact, Black 
is slightly for choice in this position.} *

