1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nxc6 {This is relatively rare, but 
it has still been played a couple thousand times so it's worth knowing how to 
deal with it.} bxc6 {[%cal Bd7d5][%csl Gc6,Gd7,Ge6] It is rarely a good idea to 
recapture with the d-pawn when a queen exchange is on the cards.} 6. Bd3 {[%cal 
Gd3h7,Be4e5,Be4d5] The best square for the bishop, seeing as the e4-pawn might 
advance to e5 or be exchanged on d5.} Nf6 {[%cal Bd8a5,Ga5e5,Ga5e1]} ({Note 
that} Nf6 7. e5 {fails due to} 7... Qa5+ {.}) 7. O-O d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6,Gc6] 
Black stakes out his central claim.} 8. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] Defending the pawn in 
this way avoids ...d4.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7e5] A flexible move that prevents e5 for 
now.} 9. f4 {[%cal Be4e5] White prepares e5 with the idea of a future kingside 
offensive perhaps, with f5.} h5 $11 {[%cal Bf6g4,Bf8c5,Bc7b6,Gh5g4][%csl 
Rg1,Rf2,Re3,Gg4]} ({Not the most common move, but probably the strongest! ...h5 
is an idea which features regularly in many Taimanov variations. Besides the 
obvious idea of ...h5-h4-h3 at some point, in this position ...h5 exploits the 
dark squares which White weakened with his previous move. All of a sudden 
...Qb6+ or ...Bc5+ followed by ...Ng4 looks like a bit of a problem for White. 
With correct play, like} h5 10. Qf3 Bb7 {etc., this position is roughly equal.}) 
*

