1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7][%csl 
Rd6,Rc7]} ({This is White's second most popular fifth move - after the very 
natural mainline of} 5. Nc3 {.}) {The idea behind 5. Nb5 is to simply exploit 
the dark square weaknesses Black has on d6 and c7. The downside to this, 
however, is that White's knight on b5 is rather vulnerable and is prone to being 
kicked around with ...a6.} d6 {Black has very little choice but to deal with the 
dark-squared holes with ...d6. This is a concession, as typically in the 
Taimanov Black prefers to leave his pawn on d7 (this allows him to potentially 
play the ...d5 break in a single move and develop the dark-squared bishop 
outside the pawn chain). However, as previously mentioned, White has made a 
concession of his own - the time wasting manoeuvre of Nd4-b5 and then to a3 or 
c3 (after ...a6) gives Black time to comfortably solve his opening problems.} 6. 
Bf4 {[%cal Gf4d6,Gb5d6,Gd1d6][%csl Rd6]} ({White takes a different approach in 
this variation than the one after} 6. c4 {. Instead of heading towards a Maroczy 
structure, White uses his extra tempo to try take advantage of the knight on b5 
by forcing more concessions on the dark squares from Black. The d6-pawn is now 
obviously under attack and the only way to defend it is to advance.}) e5 {[%csl 
Rf4]} ({The only decent way to defend d6.} 6... Ne5 {is asking for trouble 
after} 7. N1a3 {and Nc4.}) 7. Be3 {[%csl Rd5,Rd6] White has lost a tempo in 
order to provoke the e-pawn's advance. This is in order to further weaken the 
d6-pawn and create a weakness on d5 which could potentially become an outpost 
for one of White's minor pieces.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4] Natural 
development.} 8. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Bb1c3,Bc3d5][%csl Rf6,Gd5] White moves the 
bishop for a third time (!) but it does have a point to it - the knight is one 
of the defenders of the kingside and controls the d5-square. And by removing it, 
White clears the way for d5 becoming a strong outpost for one of White's minor 
pieces.} a6 {Kicking the knight back.} 9. Bxf6 ({White takes now so that 
capturing with the queen is impossible -} 9. Bxf6 9... Qxf6 $2 10. Nc7+ {.}) 
gxf6 10. N5c3 f5 $11 {[%cal Gf5e4,Bc8e6,Bf8g7,Be8g8][%csl Re4] While some people 
might be put off by the doubled f-pawns, it really is nothing to worry about 
since we just carried out the ...f5 freeing break. This break rids black of his 
doubled pawns and loosens White's grip on the d5-square by exchanging the 
e4-pawn. Black's d5-hole is offset by his bishop pair.} *

