1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nb5 ({This is White's second most 
popular fifth move - after the very natural mainline of} 5. Nc3 {.}) {The idea 
behind 5. Nb5 is to simply exploit the dark square weaknesses Black has on d6 
and c7. The downside to this, however, is that White's knight on b5 is rather 
vulnerable and is prone to being kicked around with ...a6.} d6 {Black has very 
little choice but to deal with the dark-squared holes with ...d6. This is a 
concession, as typically in the Taimanov Black prefers to leave his pawn on d7 
(this allows him to potentially play the ...d5 break in a single move and 
develop the dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain). However, as previously 
mentioned, White has made a concession of his own - the time wasting manoeuvre 
of Nd4-b5 and then to a3 or c3 (after ...a6) gives Black time to comfortably 
solve his opening problems.} 6. c4 {White opts for a Maroczy structure (which is 
characterised by the c4- and e4-pawns). While some people enjoy facing it and 
adopt the Hedgehog structure, it can be quite polarising and is certainly not to 
everyone's tastes. Fortunately, a better alternative exists which makes use of 
White's wandering knight.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4] Attacking e4.} 7. N1c3 
({Note that} 7. N5c3 {would simply be a better version of virtually the same 
thing for Black, as he would save a tempo by not playing ...a6.}) a6 {[%csl 
Rb5]} 8. Na3 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ga5e1,Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} ({This is an exceedingly rare 
move which, at the time of writing, has only been played 13 times! The most 
popular options,} 8... Be7) ({and} 8... b6 {, have been featured in around 3000 
games.}) {Besides the usual benefits of playing an unusual line (avoid 
preparation, element of surprise etc.), this move is actually very strong! It 
was not only the choice of the very strong GMs Vachier Lagraeve and Edouard, but 
it is favoured by engines as well. So why hasn't it caught on? It is quite a 
strange-looking move and it does break the fundamental opening principle of not 
developing your queen too early. Unless the black player specifically prepared 
this move, it is unlikely that he would find it over the board. The idea behind 
it is perfectly logical. White has wasted time with the Nd4-b5-a3 manoeuvre, so 
Black tries to exploit his lead in development by laying siege to White's 
centre. At the moment, e4 is attacked.} 9. Bd2 {[%csl Rd2] This is White's most 
common move and a natural choice. It is already a concession though, which just 
shows how disruptive Black's previous move is. The bishop is far from ideally 
placed on d2 and instead would rather be developed to e3. Now the worst case 
scenario for Black is that he drops his queen back to c7 while White develops 
his bishop to e3, thus reaching a fairly standard position which is OK for 
black.} Be7 {Note that the discovered attack on Black's queen which looks 
dangerous (Nb5 or Nd5) is in fact totally harmless.} 10. Be2 ({A natural move 
and White's most common choice by far, but perhaps} 10. Bd3 {is a bit better to 
protect e4.}) O-O 11. O-O Qe5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ge5e4][%csl Re4] Black again exploits 
the poorly defended e4 pawn. Note how f4 is met with a check on d4.} 12. Bf3 
(12. Bd3 {is met by the unpleasant} 12... Nb4 {.}) Nd4 $11 {[%cal 
Bd4f3,Bc8d7,Bd7c6][%csl Rf3] Black has infiltrated White's dark squares and the 
upcoming exchange on f3 will alleviate some of his space issues while picking up 
the bishop pair. Black has fully equalised here.} *

