1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 {A natural move and White's 
main choice, as we shall see in the coming trainable variations.} Qc7 {Black 
remains flexible - some of the deeper reasoning behind this move is explained in 
the next lines.} 6. Ndb5 {[%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d6][%csl Rc7] A rare move (it was only 
played in just under 5% of the games in this position) . However, it certainly 
does look quite scary if unprepared. Fortunately Black is totally OK with a bit 
of knowledge. While the variation is rather long, it is also quite forced, which 
makes it a bit simpler to memorise. White hits Black's queen and intends to 
exploit the weakened dark squares.} Qb8 {[%cal Gb8d6,Gf8d6,Ba7a6] The logical 
retreat, to control d6.} 7. Be3 a6 {Kicking the knight backwards makes sense.} 
8. Bb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c7,Bc3b5,Ba6b5,Gb5c7][%csl Rc7] White has to take up the 
challenge in order to justify his previous opening play. White sacrifices a 
piece to gain some more control over Black's weak dark squares.} axb5 9. Nxb5 
{[%cal Gb5c7][%csl Re8]} Bb4+ {[%cal Bb4a5,Ga5c7] The bishop is heading to a5 so 
that it can assist in the defence of c7.} 10. c3 Ba5 11. Nc7+ {Thing's certainly 
look scary for Black, but there's nothing to fear here:} Qxc7 $1 {An important 
move to remember! Black sacrifices his queen to shore up the dark squares holes 
once and for all.} 12. Bxc7 Bxc7 {The material situation is roughly even. 3 
minor pieces (together with the bishop pair) are equivalent to the queen and 
pawn which White has, especially in this middlegame situation where many pieces 
still remain.} 13. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4g7][%csl Rg7] White tries to exploit Black's 
uncastled king.} Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7,Bg7g6]} ({Black protects g7 with his king. One 
of the main alternatives is} 13... Be5 {, which is the recommendation in 'The 
Most Flexible Sicilian'. Of course it is also a good option which scores well in 
practice. I prefer 13... Kf8 slightly due to the simplicity of its idea. 13... 
Be5 works well against} 14. f4 {,} ({but I think if White simply plays} 14. Bb5 
{and then castles the bishop is a bit oddly placed on e5.})) {The idea behind 
...Kf8 is simply to castle 'artificially' with ...g6 and ...Kg7.} 14. Bb5 g6 15. 
O-O Kg7 $11 {[%cal Bg8f6,Bd7d5] Black has 'castled'. Next he will play ...Nf6 
and ...d5 with complete equality.} *

