[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287259"]

1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. g3 {[%cal Bf1g2,Gg2a8][%csl Ra8] The Fianchetto System is probably 
one of the most universal systems - virtually every opening features a 
Fianchetto variation somewhere! They have a reputation for being solid 
variations which are often not too critical for the opponent, but remain tricky 
to deal with. In the Taimanov, the Fianchetto variation is particularly 
irritating because generic play by Black can quickly land him in hot water. The 
bishop on g2 is well-poised to cause problems for Black on the long diagonal 
after ...b5.} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Bb7b5] The normal Taimanov move - covering b5 
against possible knight invasions while preparing a possible ...b5 in the 
future.} 7. Bg2 Nge7 {[%cal Bc6d4,Ge7c6][%csl Bd4]} ({This strange-looking move 
is Black's third most common choice, but it is way behind the most common 
choices of} 7... d6) ({and} 7... Nf6 {.}) {So what is the idea here? It appears 
as if Black is simply blocking in his own bishop. Since White has taken a bit of 
time to develop his light-squared bishop to g2, Black has a chance to develop 
his own threats and play. The fundamental idea behind ...Nge7 is to capture the 
knight on d4 and follow up with ...Nc6. This little idea has a handful of ideas 
- Black develops his kingside knight with tempo, exchanges White's developed 
knight and thus reduces the inherent disadvantage of having less space. 
Additionally, by not having a knight on f6 Black is less vulnerable to possible 
e4-e5 ideas.} ({While this idea is relatively rare, it is quite strong and has 
been played by a host of top players such as Laznicka, Morozevich and Granda 
Zuniga. Another interesting idea is} 7... h5 {in this position, which was one of 
the recommendations for Black in 'The Most Flexible Sicilian'.}) 8. Nb3 {White's 
most common choice and the most obvious 'counter' to Black's idea. Black 
obviously can't take on d4 now, so an alternative plan must be implemented. 
Seeing as Nb3 doesn't really further White's own development, Black has time to 
do this.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Bc6e5,Be5c4,Ge7c6][%csl Bc6] Black's knight heads for 
the fantastic c4 outpost, where it will dominate White's dark-squared bishop on 
c1. This has the additional benefit of freeing the c6 square for the second 
knight.} 9. f4 {[%cal Gf4e5][%csl Re5]} Nc4 {[%cal Gc4b2,Gc4e3,Bb7b5][%csl 
Rc1,Gc4] The knight is well-placed here - it attacks b2 and controls e3, thus 
limiting the effectiveness of White's c1-bishop. The c4-square is however quite 
unstable, since only the queen supports the knight. As a result we intend to 
reinforce the outpost with ...b5.} 10. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3c4] A natural choice 
applying some light pressure to the c4-knight.} b5 {[%cal Gb5c4][%csl Gc4] 
Supporting the knight.} 11. Nd4 Nc6 $11 {[%cal Bc6d4,Bf8c5,Bc8b7]} ({Black's 
second knight reaches its destination where it will be exchanged soon and 
alleviate Black's space issues. With his strong knight on c4 and having solved 
his space issues, Black is doing well.} 11... Bb7 {is a decent alternative as 
played by Adhiban.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto System: 8. 0-0"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287260"]

1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. g3 {The Fianchetto System is probably one of the most universal 
systems - virtually every opening features a Fianchetto variation somewhere! 
They have a reputation for being solid variations which are often not too 
critical for the opponent, but remain tricky to deal with. In the Taimanov, the 
Fianchetto variation is particularly irritating because generic play by Black 
can quickly land him in hot water. The bishop on g2 is well-poised to cause 
problems for Black on the long diagonal after ...b5.} a6 {The normal Taimanov 
move - covering b5 against possible knight invasions while preparing a possible 
...b5 in the future.} 7. Bg2 Nge7 ({This strange-looking move is Black's third 
most common choice, but it is way behind the most common choices of} 7... d6) 
({and} 7... Nf6 {.}) {So what is the idea here? It appears as if Black is simply 
blocking in his own bishop. Since White has taken a bit of time to develop his 
light-squared bishop to g2, Black has a chance to develop his own threats and 
play. The fundamental idea behind ...Nge7 is to capture the knight on d4 and 
follow up with ...Nc6. This little idea has a handful of ideas - Black develops 
his kingside knight with tempo, exchanges White's developed knight and thus 
reduces the inherent disadvantage of having less space. Additionally, by not 
having a knight on f6 Black is less vulnerable to possible e4-e5 ideas.} ({While 
this idea is relatively rare, it is quite strong and has been played by a host 
of top players such as Laznicka, Morozevich and Granda Zuniga. Another 
interesting idea is} 7... h5 {in this position, which was one of the 
recommendations for Black in 'The Most Flexible Sicilian'.}) 8. O-O {This 
natural move is White's second most common choice, but it allows Black to carry 
out his idea without a hitch.} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4][%csl Rd4] The 
queen is uncomfortably short of good retreat squares.} 10. Qe3 {[%cal 
Gc1e3][%csl Rc1] This is probably the relatively best retreat square, but it 
still blocks the c1-bishop.} h5 $11 {[%cal Bh5h4,Bh4g3,Gh8h5] Once again we see 
this standard Taimanov idea in action. It is especially effective against 
fianchettos. Black wants to activate his rook on the h-file after a ...h4xg3 
break. With a pair of knights exchanged, Black has alleviated his space problems 
and equalised comfortably.} *

