1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be2 {Be2 systems are just as universal and prevalent in the Sicilian 
as the Fianchetto Systems. White simply wants to complete development with 
natural moves such as O-O, Be3 etc. His flexibility then allows him to choose 
from a number of plans. Together with the English Attack and fashionable 7. Qf3, 
this is one of the more challenging setups White has it his disposal.} a6 {A 
standard move covering b5.} 7. O-O (7. Be3 {will simply transpose after} 7... 
Nf6 ({although another interesting option is} 7... b5 {.})) Nf6 {Natural 
development. Black targets the e4-pawn.} 8. Be3 Bb4 {The bishop is developed 
actively and Black threatens the e4-pawn.} 9. Na4 {White moves to take advantage 
of Black's weakened dark squares. Play becomes rather concrete now.} Be7 ({Note 
that taking on e4 is a blunder -} 9... Nxe4 $2 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qd4 {forks 
Black's minor pieces.}) 10. Nxc6 {Exchanging the knight on d4 unveils the bishop 
which controls some of Black's weakened dark squares.} bxc6 11. Nb6 Rb8 12. Nxc8 
Qxc8 {White has gained the bishop pair, but Black's bishop on c8 was a bad one 
in any case.} 13. Bd4 {[%cal Gd4b2,Gd4g7] White's most challenging option here. 
The bishop protects b2 and prevents ...Nxe4.} c5 {[%csl Rd4] Kicking the bishop 
around.} 14. Be5 {[%cal Ge5b8][%csl Rb8]} Rb6 {[%cal Bd7d6,Gb6d6][%csl Re5] From 
here the rook prepares ...d6 to push the bishop back.} 15. Qd3 d6 16. Bc3 O-O 
$11 {[%cal Bf6d7,Be7f6] Black has developed quite harmoniously. The position is 
relatively balanced - Black should try avoid opening the position too much in 
order to prevent White's bishop pair from becoming even more dangerous.} *

