[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287264"]

1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {[%cal Bd1d2,Be1c1,Bf2f3,Bg2g4] The English Attack is white's 
most popular weapon against the Taimanov. This is understandable, since the 
setup is easy to remember and aggressive. White's development scheme is similar 
to that of the Yugoslav Attack (in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, 
g4 etc.} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5][%csl Gb5] The standard Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. 
Bd3 {This natural developing move is bundled together with the English Attack 
(even though it isn't technically the English attack) since it probably isn't 
dangerous enough to warrant its own special name. White simply develops and 
defends e4.} Nf6 8. O-O Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gc7h2][%csl Rh2] Not the most common move, 
but a strong one and an idea you should definitely be familiar with. It might 
seem strange to block Black's d7-pawn, but this is only temporary. The bishop on 
d6 disrupts White and forces some sort of concession.} 9. h3 ({Note how Black's 
bishop development can't be exploited by} 9. f4 {due to the weakness of the 
a7-g1 diagonal and the fact that the pawn would hang after} 9... Nxd4 {.}) O-O 
10. Nxc6 {It's not easy for White to make progress otherwise. The bishop on d6 
is very disruptive. Black was planning to simply complete development with ...b5 
and ...Bb7.} dxc6 11. f4 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Ge5,Rf4] In these structures, the most 
important thing is to not allow White to play e5 himself.} 12. f5 b5 $11 {[%cal 
Bc8b7,Bc7e7,Bd6c5,Ge7d6] This is a rather standard structure which is totally 
fine for Black.} *

