a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {The English Attack is white's most popular weapon against the 
Taimanov. This is understandable, since the setup is easy to remember and 
aggressive. White's development scheme is similar to that of the Yugoslav Attack 
(in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, g4 etc.} a6 {The standard 
Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. Qd2 {[%cal Be1c1] White prepares to castle long 
and then roll his pawns forward on the kingside.} Nf6 8. f4 {The f4 idea can be 
tried in a number of different positions. In this situation it is weakening the 
light squares which can be exploited.} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl 
Rd2,Re1,Re4] The bishop develops actively, pinning White's knight and attacking 
e4. If the e-pawn advances then the knight hops into d5.} 9. Bd3 {White is 
forced to defend the e-pawn.} Na5 $1 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gc7c3][%csl Rc3] Black takes 
his opportunity to put more pressure on knight on c3. Now doubled c-pawns are 
virtually unavoidable.} 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 $11 {[%cal 
Ga5c4,Gf6e4][%csl Gc4,Ge4] White's bishop pair are compensated by White's 
wrecked pawn structure. Black's knights will be getting good squares on e4 and 
c4 within a few moves.} *

