[Site "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Attack: 9. f4"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287266"]

1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {The English Attack is white's most popular weapon against the 
Taimanov. This is understandable, since the setup is easy to remember and 
aggressive. White's development scheme is similar to that of the Yugoslav Attack 
(in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, g4 etc.} a6 {The standard 
Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. Qd2 {White prepares to castle long and then roll 
his pawns forward on the kingside.} Nf6 8. O-O-O {[%cal Bf2f3,Bg2g4,Bg4g5] White 
castles long with the intention of throwing pawns at Black's kingside - f3 and 
g4-g5 are coming up.} Be7 (8... Bb4 {is the more popular choice, but in recent 
years the Taimanov has experienced a revival largely thanks to discoveries in 
this 8... Be7 variation.}) 9. f4 {This is a possibility once again - and once 
again the issue here are the weakened light squares (e4 and d5).} b5 {[%cal 
Bb5b4,Gf6e4][%csl Rc3,Re4] Black doesn't want to play ...Bb4 this time (since 
there's no need to move the bishop twice) - instead, the support for the e4 pawn 
will be dislodged by playing ...b5-b4.} 10. e5 {This is critical of course.} b4 
$1 {[%csl Rc3] An important counterattack to remember - the mild complications 
work in Black's favour.} 11. exf6 bxc3 12. Qxc3 Bxf6 {[%cal 
Gc6d4,Gf6d4,Gc3c7][%csl Rc6,Rd4] Material is level.} 13. g4 {[%cal Bg4g5]} h6 
$11 {[%cal Bc8b7,Ba8c8,Gh6g5][%csl Gg5] Black secures the bishops position on 
the vital a1-h8 diagonal. Once ...Bb7 has been played, all of Black's pieces 
will have good squares.} *

