1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {The English Attack is White's most popular weapon against the 
Taimanov. This is understandable, since the setup is easy to remember and 
aggressive. White's development scheme is similar to that of the Yugoslav Attack 
(in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, g4 etc.} a6 {The standard 
Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. Qd2 {White prepares to castle long and then roll 
his pawns forward on the kingside.} Nf6 8. O-O-O {White castles long with the 
intention of throwing pawns at Black's kingside - f3 and g4-g5 are coming up.} 
Be7 (8... Bb4 {is the more popular choice, but in recent years the Taimanov has 
experienced a revival largely thanks to discoveries in this 8... Be7 
variation.}) 9. f3 {This move succeeds where f4 ideas fail: the light squares, 
starting with e4, are bolstered by the f3-pawn. Clearly this rules out an f-pawn 
rush from White, but it introduces a different pawn storm idea: g4-g5.} b5 {Not 
only does this move facilitate the development of Black's light-squared bishop, 
but in certain positions having ...b4 available is very useful.} 10. g4 (10. Kb1 
{will probably transpose after} 10... Bb7 11. g4 {.}) ({Taking on c6 before 
playing g4 is not dangerous - simply play} 10. Nxc6 dxc6 {followed by exchanging 
major pieces along the d-file.}) Nxd4 $1 {This idea has been credited for 
revitalising the Be7 variation. It is the recommendation for Black in 'The Most 
Flexible Sicilian' as well as Van Kampen's Taimanov series on Chess24. Black 
delays castling, thus neutering White's kingside attack. Additionally Black 
intends to get central counterplay by play ...Bb7 followed by ...d5 (possibly 
with ...e5 first) .} 11. Bxd4 {The more common and natural recapture White has 
at his disposal.} Bb7 ({Natural development - a relatively unexplored 
alternative is} 11... b4 {.}) 12. g5 {[%cal Gd1d7][%csl Rf6,Rd7] White's most 
common move and also the critical test of Black's idea (because of White's next 
move). The pawn attacks the knight and removes a defender from the d7-pawn.} Nh5 
13. Be5 $1 {[%cal Ge5c7,Gd1d7][%csl Rc7,Rd7] A funny little tactical idea. White 
is removing the defender of the d7-pawn by sacrificing a bishop (which he will 
regain on b7 though).} Qxe5 {Fortunately there is no reason for Black not to 
play along.} 14. Qxd7+ Kf8 15. Qxb7 Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b7] Black can alternatively 
take on g5 first, which is the recommendation in 'The Most Flexible Sicilian'. 
Instead, Van Kampen recommends playing for activity by leaving the pawn alone 
for now - while both options might be objectively very similar, I prefer Van 
Kampen's choice.} 16. Rd7 {White chooses to activate his rook rather than cling 
on to his extra pawn.} Qxb7 17. Rxb7 h6 $1 {[%cal Gh8h2][%csl Gh8] Black insists 
on giving up the pawn for the activity of the rook on h8.} 18. g6 $1 {If White 
took on h6, Black's active rooks and White's weak pawns would provide ample 
compensation for the pawn.} fxg6 {[%cal Bf8f7,Gh8d8,Gd8c8] White has managed to 
mess up Black's pawn structure slightly, but it doesn't matter since Black's 
king is nearby to cover the weaknesses. Black's king has f7 available to him 
now, which means the rook on h8 can easily be activated.} 19. a4 Kf7 $11 {[%cal 
Ga8a1,Bh8b8][%csl Rc1]} ({Note that White can't take the b5 pawn immediately 
because of problems down the a-file. Instead, after} Kf7 20. Kb1 {Black will 
exchange rooks with} 20... Rhb8 {and totally equalise.}) *

