revitalising the Be7 variation. It is the recommendation for Black in 'The Most 
Flexible Sicilian' as well as Van Kampen's Taimanov series on Chess24. Black 
delays castling, thus neutering White's kingside attack. Additionally Black 
intends to get central counterplay by play ...Bb7 followed by ...d5 (possibly 
with ...e5 first) .} 11. Bxd4 {The more common and natural recapture White has 
at his disposal.} Bb7 ({Natural development - a relatively unexplored 
alternative is} 11... b4 {.}) 12. g5 {White's most common move and also the 
critical test of Black's idea (because of White's next move). The pawn attacks 
the knight and removes a defender from the d7-pawn.} Nh5 13. Be5 $1 {A funny 
little tactical idea. White is removing the defender of the d7-pawn by 
sacrificing a bishop (which he will regain on b7 though).} Qxe5 {Fortunately 
there is no reason for Black not to play along.} 14. Qxd7+ Kf8 15. Qxb7 Qb8 $1 
{Black can alternatively take on g5 first, which is the recommendation in 'The 
Most Flexible Sicilian'. Instead, Van Kampen recommends playing for activity by 
leaving the pawn alone for now - while both options might be objectively very 
similar, I prefer Van Kampen's choice.} 16. Qxb8+ Rxb8 17. h4 {White can hold 
onto the pawn, but Black gets a huge amount of activity in return, for example:} 
h6 $1 {[%cal Bh6g5,Gh8h1][%csl Rg5]} 18. Ne2 {Taking on h6 instead just frees 
Black's rook and leaves h4 weak.} hxg5 19. hxg5 g6 {[%cal Bf8g7] Once again, 
Black is playing for activity instead of material.} 20. f4 {[%cal Gf4g5]} Kg7 
21. Kb1 Rbd8 $11 {[%cal Ge2f4,Be6e5][%csl Rf4,Rg5] White's pieces are tied down 
to the defence of the pawns while Black is active and has full compensation.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fashionable"]
[Black "7. Qf3: 11. Qg3 1"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287274"]

1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {The English Attack is White's most popular weapon against the 
Taimanov. This is understandable, since the setup is easy to remember and 
aggressive. White's development scheme is similar to that of the Yugoslav Attack 
(in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, g4 etc.} a6 {The standard 
Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3e4,Bf3g3,Gg3g7,Be1c1][%csl Rg7] 
This variation has been highly popular in the last few years at the top level, 
so I thought it was worth dedicating a few lines to combating it. White's idea 
is to long castle and then possibly put pressure on g7 with Qg3. Additionally 
the queen supports the light squares in the centre which come under fire in many 
other cases.} Nf6 ({Black has tried numerous other moves at this point. This is 
Black's most popular choice and I also think it is one of the best (based on the 
idea on the next move). Van Kampen recommended} 7... d6 {in his video series.}) 
8. O-O-O Nxd4 $1 {I think this move equalises for Black, or at least comes very 
close to it. Black transforms the pawn structure quickly into one where White's 
queen might not be so well-placed on f3.} 9. Bxd4 e5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Ge5,Rf3]} 10. 
Be3 d6 {[%cal Bc8g4,Gg4d1][%csl Rf3] By transforming the pawn structure into the 
e5 + d6 one, a lot of White's dynamic attacking ideas are neutralised and 
White's queen becomes a little misplaced on f3. Usually the queen would be on 
the d-file, assisting the assault on the d6-pawn and d5-weakness, whereas now 
the d6-pawn isn't under too much threat. Additionally ...Bg4 is threatened now.} 
11. Qg3 {White can also play this on the 10th move, which would transpose to 
this position.} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black needs to take the d5-square under his 
control.} 12. Bg5 {[%cal Bg5f6,Gc3d5][%csl Gd5]} Be7 13. Bxf6 {Removing a 
defender of the d5-square.} Bxf6 14. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5]} Bxd5 15. Rxd5 O-O $11 
{[%cal Gf6e7,Bb7b5,Bb5b4,Ba6a5][%csl Bf6,Rf1] This position is equal, but fairly 
lifeless unfortunately. Black will probably have to advance his queenside pawns 
to get some play. While the d6-pawn is backward, Black can always defend it with 
ease due to the opposite coloured bishops.} *

