1. e4 c5 ({Of the two main responses to 1. e4 - the other being} 1... e5 {, the 
Sicilian tends to offer sharper and more unbalanced play. The majority of 
Sicilians are concrete in nature, and although ideas play a large role, 
theoretical knowledge is just as important.}) 2. Nf3 e6 ({The Taimanov can also 
be reached via a} 2... Nc6 {move order, but 2... e6 has the advantage of dodging 
the irritating Rossolimo Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Bb5 {.}) 3. d4 {This is by far 
White's most common move which signifies the beginning of the Open Sicilian. The 
Open Sicilian is characterised by d4 and is regarded as the critical test to all 
Sicilians. Open Sicilians are highly theoretical and typically require plenty of 
memorisation. As a result, players sometimes opt for an Anti-Sicilian. Their 
primary goal is to dodge the huge body of theory in mainline Sicilians and as a 
result they usually are especially popular amongst club players. We'll be 
examining some of the Anti-Sicilians in the final lines of this course.} cxd4 4. 
Nxd4 Nc6 ({This move characterises the Taimanov Sicilian. Alternatively,} 4... 
a6 {leads to the Sicilian Kan. The primary difference between them is that in 
the Kan the queen's knight remains flexible and is often deployed to d7, whereas 
in the Taimanov the knight heads for c6.}) 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The queen's position is 
improved while Black remains flexible, allowing him to adapt to White's chosen 
setup.} 6. Be3 {The English Attack is White's most popular weapon against the 
Taimanov. This is understandable, since the setup is easy to remember and 
aggressive. White's development scheme is similar to that of the Yugoslav Attack 
(in the Sicilian Dragon) - Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, f3, g4 etc.} a6 {The standard 
Taimanov move covering b5.} 7. Qf3 {This variation has been highly popular in 
the last few years at the top level, so I thought it was worth dedicating a few 
lines to combating it. White's idea is to long castle and then possibly put 
pressure on g7 with Qg3. Additionally the queen supports the light squares in 
the centre which come under fire in many other cases.} Nf6 ({Black has tried 
numerous other moves at this point. This is Black's most popular choice and I 
also think it is one of the best (based on the idea on the next move). Van 
Kampen recommended} 7... d6 {in his video series.}) 8. O-O-O Nxd4 $1 {I think 
this move equalises for Black, or at least comes very close to it. Black 
transforms the pawn structure quickly into one where White's queen might not be 
so well-placed on f3.} 9. Bxd4 e5 $1 10. Be3 d6 {By transforming the pawn 
structure into the e5 + d6 one, a lot of White's dynamic attacking ideas are 
neutralised and White's queen becomes a little misplaced on f3. Usually the 
queen would be on the d-file, assisting the assault on the d6-pawn and 
d5-weakness, whereas now the d6-pawn isn't under too much threat. Additionally 
...Bg4 is threatened now.} 11. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Bg2g4][%csl Gg4] White nips 
...Bg4 in the bud and prepares g4.} b5 {[%cal Bb5b4,Bc8b7] Preparing ...b4 and 
maybe the development of the light-squared bishop to b7.} 12. g4 {White carries 
out his main offensive idea, but maybe a bit too soon.} b4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Re4] 
The knight is pretty much forced to d5 - otherwise e4 becomes too weak.} 13. Nd5 
Nxd5 14. exd5 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ba6a5,Bc8a6,Ga6f1] The exchange has eased Black's 
space problem and solved the issue of the d5-outpost. Next Black should exchange 
light-squared bishops with ...a5 followed by ...Ba6.} *

