1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {A flexible move, which can lead to the Grand Prix, the Closed 
Sicilian or transpose later to an open Sicilian.} ({White has a number of 
Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you with a more comprehensive 
repertoire, we have covered some of White's most common choices, however some of 
white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted 
since they are rarely seen.}) e6 3. g3 {[%cal Bf1g2,Bd2d3] The Closed Sicilian 
is characterised by Nc3 with a kingside fianchetto.} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gd5d4] The 
best way to counter White's rather timid play is with a central pawn break.} 4. 
exd5 {White's most common choice but sometimes White opts to decline the 
exchange and head for KIA-style positions. However, once Black has been allowed 
to play ...d4 he has no real problems.} exd5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg2d5,Gc3d5][%csl 
Rd5] Developing and attacking d5.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6d5]} 6. d3 Be7 {Natural 
development here is good.} 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O d4 {[%csl Rc3] Forcing an exchange 
on e4.} 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Bd7f6,Gf6e4,Bf8e8][%csl Re4] 
Preparing to put the knight on f6. Black has achieved easy equality.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Sicilians: The"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287278"]

1. e4 c5 ({White has a number of Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you 
with a more comprehensive repertoire, we have covered some of White's most 
common choices, however some of white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 
c5 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted since they are rarely seen.}) 2. Nc3 {A flexible 
move, which can lead to the Grand Prix, the Closed Sicilian or transpose later 
to an open Sicilian.} e6 3. f4 {[%cal Bg1f3,Bf1b5,Bf1c4,Be1g1,Bd1e1,Be1h4,Bf4f5] 
The Grand Prix Attack. This is a common choice of club players since White's 
play is rather straightforward to understand (especially in the ...g6 
variations) - white dreams of Qe1, f5, Qh4, Bh6 and Ng5 with mate soon to 
follow.} Nc6 {[%cal Bd7d5] In contrast to the fianchetto variations, here Black 
will be going for a central strategy with ...d5.} 4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb5 {[%cal 
Gb5e8][%csl Rc6] The most challenging move by far. Rapid development together 
with the pin put some pressure on Black.} Nge7 $1 {[%cal Ba7a6,Ge7c6][%csl Gc6] 
Black intends to solve his problems by forcing a capture on c6 and recapturing 
with his knight so as to avoid doubled pawns. If all goes according to plan, 
Black's dark-squared bishop won't be blocked in for long.} 6. exd5 {Otherwise 
Black carries out his idea of forcing the exchange on c6 with ...a6.} exd5 7. 
Qe2 $1 {[%cal Ge2e8,Gb5c6][%csl Rc6,Re7] The critical move. It poses Black the 
question: how exactly is he going to finish his development? Otherwise Black 
goes for ...a6 and then simply recaptures with the knight.} f6 {[%cal 
Gf6e5,Gf6g5,Be8f7] Possibly the only move where Black can safely claim equality. 
The idea is of course to step out of the pin with ...Kf7. The f6-pawn also does 
a great job of covering the e5 and g5 squares.} 8. Bxc6+ {White decides to use 
the pin by damaging Black's pawn structure.} bxc6 9. O-O Kf7 {[%cal Be7f5,Bf8d6] 
The king steps out of the pin, allowing the knight to move and unclog Black's 
kingside.} 10. d3 Nf5 $11 {[%cal Bf8d6,Bh8e8] Followed by ...Bd6 and ...Re8. 
Black has completed development and has a good position.} *

