1. e4 c5 ({White has a number of Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you 
with a more comprehensive repertoire, we have covered some of White's most 
common choices, however some of white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 
c5 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted since they are rarely seen.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 
{[%cal Bb1d2,Gd2e4] The slightly more popular King's Indian Attack move order. 
It has the advantage of being able to meet ...d5 with Nbd2, but it also loses 
the option of d4 in one go.} Nc6 4. g3 Nge7 ({A move order that prevents a few 
extra options White gets after} 4... g6 {.}) 5. Bg2 g6 {[%cal Bf8g7,Gg7a1][%csl 
Gg7] The kingside fianchetto is the most harmonious way for Black to develop 
here.} 6. O-O Bg7 7. c3 {[%cal Bd3d4]} O-O {This is more flexible than the 
immediate ...e5 and can lead to more double-edged positions when White plays 
d4.} 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5][%csl Rc5]} ({This is an alternative method of carrying 
out the d4 plan - the immediate} 8. d4 {is met strongly by} 8... d5 $1 {. 
Whether it is beneficial to include this move or not is debatable, since the 
bishop can become vulnerable on e3 to a knight on f5 and the pawn on b6 is quite 
useful.}) ({After a move like} 8. Re1 {, slow and positional play ensures after} 
8... e5 {.}) b6 {[%cal Gb6c5]} 9. d4 d5 $1 {[%cal Be4d5,Ge7d5] An important 
move. The c5 pawn does not hang since the knight recaptures on d5.} 10. e5 Nf5 
$11 {[%cal Bf7f6,Gf5e3][%csl Re5] Followed by 11... f6 with a great position for 
Black.} *

