1. e4 c5 ({White has a number of Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you 
with a more comprehensive repertoire, we have covered some of White's most 
common choices, however some of white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 
c5 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted since they are rarely seen.}) 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 
{[%cal Bc1b2,Bc2c4] A move with the two ideas of advancing e5 and/or pushing c4, 
and d4 to create a Maroczy setup. Note that for simplicity's sake we recommend 
meeting 2. b3 in a similar way - e6 followed by ...Nc6 and ...a6, after which 
White will have little choice but to transpose to this variation.} a6 {[%cal 
Bb8c6,Ga6b5][%csl Gb5] This prepares the knights development to c6 by 
eliminating white's Bb5xc6 option.} 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. c4 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7e5,Gc6e5]} 6. 
g3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} 7. e5 (7. Bxf6 {is not dangerous - after} 7... 
gxf6 {Black can castle long and launch his h-pawn down the board.}) Ng4 {[%cal 
Gg4e5,Gc6e5,Gc7e5][%csl Re5]} 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e5,Gf3e5,Gb2e5]} Nh6 $1 {[%cal 
Bh6f5,Gf5d4][%csl Gf5] The knight gets rerouted to the f5 outpost.} 9. Na3 Be7 
10. Nc2 O-O $11 {[%cal Bb7b5,Bd7d5,Bh6f5][%csl Gf5] Black now has the choice of 
playing for the ...b5 or ...d5 break. His position is good either way.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
