[White "Anti-Sicilians:"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian 1"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-taimanov-sicilian/course/7385, variation/287282"]

1. e4 c5 ({White has a number of Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you 
with a more comprehensive repertoire, we have covered some of White's most 
common choices, however some of white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 
c5 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted since they are rarely seen.}) 2. c3 {[%cal 
Bd2d4][%csl Ge4,Gd4] This is the Alapin or 2. c3 Sicilian. It is one of the most 
common Anti-Sicilians and probably also one of the most 
theoretically-challenging. White of course plans to simply take over the whole 
centre with d4.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} ({Note that black has two main 
ways to combat the Alapin: 2... d5 and 2... Nf6. The reason for no Morra Gambit 
coverage in this course is also important. Our recommendation against the Morra 
Gambit -} 1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {- is to transpose to the Alapin Sicilian 
with} 3... Nf6 {. After} 4. e5 Nd5 {we will reach a normal position in this 
variation.}) {The reason for this choice is two-fold: 1. It cuts down on theory 
to learn - the Morra Gambit is an opening with some complex theory which really 
isn't worth learning as Black. 2. It is probably one of Black's best options 
objectively. The Morra Gambit isn't such a bad opening, and the pitfalls you'll 
have to navigate as Black aren't worthwhile for a potentially very slight 
objective edge.} 3. e5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nd5 {[%cal Bd7d6][%csl Re5] Black lures 
White's pawns forward in order to target them in the future with ...d6.} 4. Nf3 
e6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 ({Immediately challenging White's centre and freeing up 
the d7 square.} 6... b6 {is another variation, and it is possible to swap ...e6 
for ...Nc6, but that is a different variation altogether.}) 7. Nc3 {This is a 
positionally dubious move since it accepts a backward pawn - White accepts this 
structural weakness with the hope exploiting his attacking possibilities though, 
which Black must carefully neutralise.} Nxc3 8. bxc3 {[%csl Rc3]} Qc7 {[%cal 
Gc7c3][%csl Rc3] Attacking c3.} 9. Bd2 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd6e5][%csl Re5] 
Chipping away at White's e5-stronghold.} 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Bd3 b6 {[%cal 
Bc8b7,Gb7g2] Delaying castling in positions such as this isn't such a bad idea, 
as White can have some unpleasant ideas of attacking h7 if Black isn't careful.} 
12. O-O Bb7 13. Re1 O-O $11 {[%cal Ba8c8,Bf8e8,Be6e5] Black is at least equal 
here, with his well-developed pieces and better pawn structure.} *

