1. e4 c5 ({White has a number of Anti-Sicilians at his disposal. To provide you 
with a more comprehensive repertoire, we have covered some of White's most 
common choices, however some of white's slightly more offbeat options - such as} 
c5 2. Na3 {- have been ommitted since they are rarely seen.}) 2. c3 {This is the 
Alapin or 2. c3 Sicilian. It is one of the most common Anti-Sicilians and 
probably also one of the most theoretically-challenging. White of course plans 
to simply take over the whole centre with d4.} Nf6 ({Note that Black has two 
main ways to combat the Alapin: 2... d5 and 2... Nf6. The reason for no Morra 
Gambit coverage in this course is also important. Our recommendation against the 
Morra Gambit -} 1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {- is to transpose to the Alapin 
Sicilian with} 3... Nf6 {. After} 4. e5 Nd5 {we will reach a normal position in 
this variation.}) {The reason for this choice is two-fold: 1. It cuts down on 
theory to learn - the Morra Gambit is an opening with some complex theory which 
really isn't worth learning as Black. 2. It is probably one of Black's best 
options objectively. The Morra Gambit isn't such a bad opening, and the pitfalls 
you'll have to navigate as Black aren't worthwhile for a potentially very slight 
objective edge.} 3. e5 Nd5 {Black lures White's pawns forward in order to target 
them in the future with ...d6.} 4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 ({Immediately 
challenging White's centre and freeing up the d7 square.} 6... b6 {is another 
variation, and it is possible to swap ...e6 for ...Nc6, but that is a different 
variation altogether.}) 7. Bc4 ({The overwhelmingly most common move. White 
develops the bishop to a natural square. The seemingly-logical alternative,} 7. 
Bd3 {is met by the highly unpleasant} 7... Nb4 $1 {.}) Nc6 {Black has no reason 
to fear Bxd5, since the pawns will be undoubled shortly.} 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 {The 
main move, although White has a number of alternatives.} O-O 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. 
bxc3 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e5,Gc6e5,Bf8d8,Ga5c3][%csl Re5,Rc3] Putting 
pressure on e5 and clearing the way for a rook on d8.} 13. Qe4 {[%cal 
Bc4d3,Gd3h7][%csl Rh7]} ({After} 13. Rb1 $6 {, we can simply grab the c3-pawn.}) 
({After} 13. a4 {, standard play ensues and it is better to leave the pawn.}) 
Qa4 $11 {[%cal Ga4e4][%csl Re4,Rc4] A vital pin to remember, which stops White's 
attack (with Bd3, etc.) in its tracks. Black is fine here.} *

